05164nam a22007935i 9780292733978DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211994txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927339787 a10.7560/7248222doi  a(DE-B1597)587959  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aQA11b.D4 7aLIT0041002bisacsh04a510.7bD48t00aMexican Literature :bA History /ced. by David William Foster. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1994  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1 Pre-Columbian Literatures -- t2 The Colonial Period -- t3 Romanticism -- t4 Nineteenth-Century Prose Fiction -- t5 Modernism -- t6 Twentieth-Century Poetry -- t7 Twentieth-Century Theater -- t8 Twentieth-Century Fiction -- t9 The Essay -- t10 Literary Theory and Criticism -- t11 Literary Reviews: A Bibliographical Essay -- t12 Mexican and Mexican American Literary Relations -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMexico has a rich literary heritage that extends back over centuries to the Aztec and Mayan civilizations. This major reference work surveys more than five hundred years of Mexican literature from a sociocultural perspective. More than merely a catalog of names and titles, it examines in detail the literary phenomena that constitute Mexico's most significant and original contributions to literature. Recognizing that no one scholar can authoritatively cover so much territory, David William Foster has assembled a group of specialists, some of them younger scholars who write from emerging trends in Latin American and Mexican literary scholarship. The topics they discuss include pre-Columbian indigenous writing (Joanna O'Connell), Colonial literature (Lee H. Dowling), Romanticism (Margarita Vargas), nineteenth-century prose fiction (Mario Martín Flores), Modernism (Bart L. Lewis), major twentieth-century genres (narrative, Lanin A. Gyurko; poetry, Adriana García; theater, Kirsten F. Nigro), the essay (Martin S. Stabb), literary criticism (Daniel Altamiranda), and literary journals (Luis Peña). Each essay offers detailed analysis of significant issues and major texts and includes an annotated bibliography of important critical sources and reference works.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMathematics teachersxTraining of. 0aMathematicsxStudy and teaching (Elementary). 0aMexican literature - History and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh1 aAltamiranda, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDowling, Lee H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, David William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, David William, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGarcia, Adriana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGyurko, Lanin A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJesus Hernandez-Gutierrez, Manuel de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Bart L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin-Flores, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNigro, Kirsten F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Connell, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPena, Luis H, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStabb, Martin S, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVargas, Margarita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/